{{coi|date=July 2018}} {{primary|date=July 2018}} {{notability|date=July 2018}} {{infobox biodatabase |title = Cellosaurus |logo = |description = '''Cellosaurus''': a knowledge resource on cell lines |scope = [[immortalised cell line|Cell lines]] |organism = [[Vertebrate]], [[Insect]], [[Tick]] |center = [[Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics]] |laboratory = CALIPHO |author = [[Amos_Bairoch]] |pmid = |released = |standard = |format = [[Flat file database]], OBO and [[XML]] |url = {{URL|https://web.expasy.org/cellosaurus/}} |download = ftp://ftp.expasy.org/databases/cellosaurus |webservice = |sql = |sparql = |webapp = Search |standalone = |license = [[Creative Commons]] Attribution-NoDerivs |versioning = Yes |frequency = 4 to 6 releases per year |curation = Yes - manual |bookmark = Yes - individual cell line entries |version = }}
'''Cellosaurus''' is an on-line knowledge resource on cell lines <ref name=Bairoch2018>{{cite journal |author=Bairoch Amos|title=The Cellosaurus, a cell-line knowledge resource |journal=Journal of Biomolecular Techniques |volume=29 |pages=1-14 |year=2018 |pmid=29805321 |doi=10.7171/jbt.18-2902-002 |issue=[Epub ahead of print |pmc=5945021}}</ref>. It is provided by the [[Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics]] (SIB) as one of its contribution <ref>https://www.elixir-europe.org/services/cellosaurus</ref>{{fv|date=July 2018}} to [[ELIXIR]]. It is the contributing resource for cell lines on the Resource Identification Portal <ref>https://scicrunch.org/resources/Cell%20Lines/source/SCR_013869-1/search?q=%2A&l=</ref>.
Its scope includes [[immortalised cell line]]s, naturally immortal cell lines (example: [[embryonic stem cell]]s) and finite life cell lines when those are distributed and used widely. The Cellosaurus provides a wealth of manually curated information; for each cell line it lists a recommended name, synonyms and the species of origin. Other types of information include standardised disease terminology (for [[cancer]] or [[genetic disorder]] cell lines), the transformant used to immortalise a cell line, transfected or knocked-out genes, microsatellite instability, doubling time, gender and age of donor (patient or animal), important sequence variations, web links, publication references and cross-references to more than 70 different databases, ontologies, cell collections and other relevant resources.
Since many cell lines used in research have been misidentified or [[Cell culture#Cell line cross-contamination|contaminated]], the Cellosaurus keeps track of problematic cell lines, including all those listed in the International Cell Line Authentication Committee (ICLAC) <ref>http://iclac.org/wp-content/uploads/Cross-Contaminations-v8_0.pdf</ref> tables.
For human as well as some dog cell lines, it provides [[short tandem repeat]] (STR) profile information.
Since July 2018, all cell lines in the Cellosaurus are represented as items in [[Wikidata]].
It is developed by [[Amos Bairoch]] at the CALIPHO group <ref>[https://www.sib.swiss/bairoch-amos-lane-lydie/amos-bairoch-lydie-lane-sub CALIPHO group], on the web site of the SIB</ref>{{fv|date=July 2018}} of the [[Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics]] (SIB).
